<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="24071">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="24071">
The type specimen, which is presumed lost or destroyed, was described from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Arcansa”">&quot;Arcansa&quot;</normalizedToken>
in 1823 by Thomas Say (
<bibRefCitation author="Rightmyer, M. G." journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="24071" pagination="1 - 170" title="A review of the cleptoparasitic bee genus Triepeolus (Hymenoptera: Apidae). Part 1" volume="1710" year="2008">Rightmyer 2008</bibRefCitation>
). However, the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Arcansas”">&quot;Arcansas&quot;</normalizedToken>
(Arkansas) of that era was a much larger piece of real estate than the Arkansas of today, then including most of what is now Oklahoma. No additional specimens from Arkansas are mentioned in 
<bibRefCitation author="Rightmyer, M. G." journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="24071" pagination="1 - 170" title="A review of the cleptoparasitic bee genus Triepeolus (Hymenoptera: Apidae). Part 1" volume="1710" year="2008">Rightmyer (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, thus we consider this specimen the first documentation of the species in Arkansas. Primary host bee is 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Svastra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Svastra atripes" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="24071" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atripes">Svastra atripes</taxonomicName>
. Opportunistic (Table 1: Site 1).
</paragraph>
